===========================================
Querying and Verifying the packages in Linux 
============================================

If the package is installed or not?


syn : rpm options <package-name>
           
                 -q(query)
                 -a (all)
                 -i (info)
                 -d (documentation)
                 -l( list all the files from that package)
                 -c ( configuration files)
                 -f ( files from which package)


# How do you know if the specified package is installed or not?
$ rpm -qa kernel

# to know how many packages are installed
$ rpm -qa

$ rpm -qa | wc -l

$ rpm -qi

Q) Can RPM automatically install missing dependencies?
NO
This dependency problem is solved by YUM

==================================================
Install, Remove and Upgrading the packages through rpm
==================================================


==> By using rpm we can install only one package at a time and it will not resolve the dependency packages.

==> We need to download from web by using wget command and install the package by rpm command.

syn: rpm options package-name
                  -i (install)
                  -v ( Verbose to see installation status)
                   -e (remove)
                   -h ( hash ###### check)
                    -U (upgrade the package)
                     
         --force (install forcefully even if it is already installed)

